kets. However, costs include origination fees, higher interest rates, and two simultaneous property payments reducing available home sale proceeds.<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/bridge-loan/"> Bridge loan calculators evaluate monthly costs</a> and break-even scenarios. Qualification requires strong credit, substantial equity, and demonstrated ability to carry both properties. Alternatives include<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/"> home equity loans</a> providing lump-sum funding and<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/"> HELOCs offering flexible credit lines</a>.</p><h3><b>What are my disclosure obligations when selling a house?</b></h3><p>Sellers must disclose known material defects affecting property value or safety per state-specific disclosure laws during the home selling process. Material defects include foundation problems, roof leaks, HVAC failures, plumbing issues, electrical hazards, pest damage, flooding history, and environmental contamination. Federal lead-based paint disclosure requirements apply to pre-1978 construction. HOA documents and special assessments require disclosure for community properties.</p><p>Non-disclosure creates legal liability for fraud even when buyers waive inspections potentially reducing home sale proceeds through litigation. Pre-listing inspections identify problems for proactive resolution.<a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/owning-a-home/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Professional inspectors evaluate properties</a> using standardized checklists covering major systems during the home selling process. Addressing issues before listing prevents negotiation obstacles. Documented repairs through licensed contractors support disclosure accuracy and buyer confidence protecting home sale proceeds.</p><p><img src="/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/ChatGPT-Image-Nov-13-2025-07_44_47-PM.png" /></p><h2><b>Conclusion: Your Path to Successful Home Sale Proceed